paper_metadata.title: MAIN TEXT
paper_metadata.extraction_summary: The paper discusses the BRCA2 variant S384F, providing details on its clinical significance, penetrance data, and individual case information.

individual_records.evidence_sentence: The variant S384F was first identified in patient 326.1, who suffered from uni-lateral breast cancer at 43 years of age.
Further analysis showed that patients 326.2 and 326.4 (uni-lateral breast cancers at 41 and 57 years of age, respectively) were also carriers of the S384F variant.
In contrast, a patient with bilateral breast cancer (ID326.3, diagnosed at 32 and 50 years of age) did not exhibit the variant.
Further analysis showed that patients 326.2 and 326.4 (uni-lateral breast cancers at 41 and 57 years of age, respectively) were also carriers of the S384F variant.

functional_data.summary: The S384F variant results in a non-conservative substitution of a hydrophilic amino acid (Ser) by a hydrophobic one (Phe).

variants.segregation_data: The variant was detected in three of the four breast cancer patients.
variants.population_frequency: Not detected in 200 healthy control women over the age of 60 years.
variants.evidence_level: Combined likelihood ratio of 1.4 × 10-8 in favour of neutrality.
variants.additional_notes: The variant is not located in a region of functional importance.
key_quotes: Our data provide conclusive evidence that the S384F variant is not a disease causing mutation.
The combined likelihood ratio of co-occurrence, co-segregation and loss of heterozygosity revealed a value of 1.4 × 10-8 in favour of neutrality of the variant.
